# Public Prosecutor _v_ Chua Chang Rong  

### \[2022\] SGDC 116

Criminal Law – theft in dwelling – theft of vibrator – criminal trespass – intent to cause alarm – mandatory treatment order – suspension order

3 June 2022

### District Judge Soh Tze Bian:

## INTRODUCTION & CHARGES

1       The accused person, Chua Chang Rong (“AP”) had previously pleaded guilty and was convicted on 23 March 2021 by a District Judge who had called for a mandatory treatment order (MTO) report on him and had heard evidence from Dr Guo Song, a psychiatrist from the Institute of Mental Health (IMH) who prepared the report and was questioned by both parties on the report[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1). But the District Judge had on 9 December 2021 rejected the AP’s plea on the basis that the third charge (MAC-905469-2020) of criminal trespass under s 447 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) (“Penal Code”) was not made out, as the AP must admit without qualifications to the fact that he had the “intent to annoy” the victim. The District Judge stated that the AP qualified the plea by taking the position that he had entered the victim’s hostel without her consent to return the vibrator, and also stated that the AP must admit that he had the “intent to annoy” the victim, in addition to intending to enter her room without consent to return the vibrator.

2       On 17 February 2022, the AP pleaded guilty before me and he was convicted of the following 3 amended charges:

> (i)      DAC-913108-2020 : “…you, sometime between 3 January 2019 to 9 January 2019, at \[XXX\] Hall in the National University of Singapore located at \[XXX\], Singapore, a building used as human dwelling, did commit theft of a pink vibrator valued at $40/-, in the possession of \[the victim\], and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 380 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed)”, with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 7 years, and shall also be liable to fine.

> (ii)      MAC-905469-2020: “…you, on 18 July 2019, at around 11.29 a.m., at the \[XXX\] Hall of the National University of Singapore, located at \[XXX\], Singapore, did commit criminal trespass, by entering the room of \[the victim\] in \[XXX\] Hall, with intent to annoy the said \[victim\], and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 447 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed)”, with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 3 months, or with fine which may extend to $1,500, or with both.

> (iii)      MAC-905470-2020 : “…you, on 22 July 2019, at around 10 p.m., at \[XXX\], Singapore, with intent to cause alarm to \[the victim\], did make insulting communication, to wit, by sending messages via a Telegram secret chat to the said victim, such as “my offer will stand whenever you’re horny and wants a real dick to satisfy you” and “I wanna save some special juice for my horny little girl”, thereby causing the said victim alarm, and you have thereby contravened Section 3(1)(b) of the Protection from Harassment Act (Cap 256A, 2015 Rev Ed), which offence is punishable under Section 3(2) of the said Act”, with a fine not exceeding $5,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 6 months or to both.

3       The AP also consented for the following charge in MAC-905468-2020 to be taken into consideration for sentencing :

> “…that you, sometime between 3 January 2019 and 9 January 2019, at \[XXX\] Hall of National University of Singapore, located at \[XXX\], Singapore, did commit criminal trespass by entering the room of \[the victim\] in \[XXX\] Hall, with intent to annoy the said \[victim\], and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 447 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed)”, with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 3 months, or with fine which may extend to $1,500, or with both.

## ISSUES FOR DETERMINATION

5       After the AP pleaded guilty and was convicted of the 3 proceeded charges, I called for a MTO report to determine his suitability for a MTO. The same IMH psychiatrist, Dr Guo Song (who had previously prepared the MTO reports on the AP for another District Judge who had set aside his plea) also prepared the MTO report and recommended that the AP be placed on a one year MTO for treatment which includes but not limited to psychotherapy, pharmacotherapy, counselling or hospitalization when necessary. Both parties questioned Dr Guo on his MTO report at the court proceedings[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2) on 23 March 2022. At the conclusion of the aforesaid court proceedings, I directed both parties to file their respective written submissions on the following issues:

> (I)     Whether MTO is an appropriate sentence to be imposed on the AP based on the reports of the IMH psychiatrist and his testimonies given in court, and why? (“ISSUE (I)”)

> (II)     If MTO is not an appropriate sentence to be imposed on the AP:

>> (A)       whether the custody threshold has been crossed based on the facts and circumstances of the present case, and why? (“ISSUE (II)(A)”)

>> (B)       what are the sentencing framework and relevant sentencing precedents as well as the aggravating and mitigating factors in the present case ? (“ISSUE (II)(B)”)

>> (C)       what will be the appropriate individual sentences to be imposed on the AP in respect of the proceeded charges and what will be an appropriate global sentence? (“ISSUE (II)(C)”)

> (III)     Pursuant to section 337(6) of the CPC, whether it will be appropriate for the court to impose individual and global sentences on the AP for the proceeded charges and suspend such sentences when a MTO is made in respect of the charges for the AP? (“Issue (III)”)

6       After careful consideration of the written submissions and replies of the parties, my determination on each of the above issues is as follows:

##### ISSUE (I)

#### Sentencing principles

7        _I accepted the Defence submissions_ that:

> (i)     the AP’s suitability for MTO is based on Dr Guo's independent professional opinion, taking into account the interviews he had with the AP and his parents, electronic medical records from IMH and the SOF and charges of the present case.

> (ii)     As regards the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders Fifth Edition ("DSM-5 "), Dr Guo had clarified that the AP had started having such "abnormality" from his adolescence—"from his young age”[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3), and also highlighted that the offences of trespass and stealing, as well as his previous incidents with swimsuits, are examples of what amounts to clinically significant distress or impairment in social, occupational, or other areas of functioning[^4].

> (iii)     Dr Guo had confirmed that while it is important for the patients to provide some form of evidence to what they declare, it is not critical.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5) The primary source of information is still based on the patient's self-report. It bears highlighting that the information was not specifically and voluntarily provided by the AP to Dr Guo who was the one who questioned him in detail, thereby coming to his conclusion.[^6]

> (iv)     Dr Guo agreed that it was harder for patients to volunteer information if they were embarrassed and he also asserted that the embarrassment is part of the disorder, and if the disorder exists within a patient such as the AP, he can and should be treated and this should not be construed as a lack of remorse.[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7)

> (v)     Little weight should be given to the medical opinion in _PP v Chong Hou En_ _<span class="citation">\[2015\] SGHC 69</span> at \[40\]_ that "_inability to resist the impulse is by definition the common core of all impulse-control disorders_”, as Dr Guo took a contrary opinion that that different patients, depending on their situation and circumstances, will experience impulsiveness differently and it will therefore not be accurate to have a blanket generalization over all paraphilic disorders. In this regard, the Prosecution also agreed and had highlighted that whether paraphilias in general can be treated must be decided "on a case-by-case basis”.[^8] In my view, the medical condition of every patient should be decided based on individual diagnosis by the expert psychiatrist or doctor.

> (vi)     The preparation of the MTO Suitability Reports for the AP was done by a team of medical experts and was not based on Dr Guo's sole decision, but after a thorough discussion with the AP’s case manager and a senior medical social worker, both of whom the AP had worked with personally as well. Both Dr Guo and his team found that the AP’s family was very supportive and they would really help in his rehabilitation.[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9)

8       However, I agreed with the Prosecution that in view of the relevant legislation and the applicable sentencing principles as well as the facts and circumstances of this case, a MTO is not an appropriate sentence to be imposed on the AP for the reasons as follows:

> (i)     There are two stages in deciding whether a MTO suitability report should be called, and whether to impose an MTO. At the first stage, in deciding whether to call for a MTO report, the court engages in a “provisional” balancing exercise of considering whether the offender “possessed sufficient rehabilitative potential”. **At the second stage, the Court decides whether a MTO should be imposed based on the same balancing exercise, but with a “higher threshold” being applied, taking into consideration the need to balance the sentencing principles of rehabilitation, deterrence, retribution, and prevention; and whether it must be “expedient” to impose MTO in that rehabilitation should be the “dominant sentencing principle” that outweighed other sentencing principles**[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10).

> (ii)      **The existence of a mental disorder on the part of the offender is always a relevant factor in the sentencing process.** The manner and extent of its relevance depend on the circumstances of each case, in particular, the nature and severity of the mental disorder. The element of general deterrence may still be accorded full weight in some circumstances, such as where the mental disorder is not serious or is not causally related to the commission of the offence, and the offence is a serious one. **In spite of the existence of a mental disorder on the part of the accused, specific deterrence may remain relevant in instances where the offence is premeditated or where there is a conscious choice to commit the offence.** If the serious psychiatric condition or mental disorder renders deterrence less effective, where for instance the offender has a significantly impaired ability to appreciate the nature and quality of his actions, then rehabilitation may take precedence. **Even though rehabilitation may be a relevant consideration, it does not necessarily dictate a light sentence. The accused could also be rehabilitated in prison.** In cases involving particularly heinous or serious offences, even when the accused person is labouring under a serious mental disorder, there is no reason why the retributive and protective principles of sentencing should not prevail over the principle of rehabilitation.[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11)(emphasis mine)

> (iii)     Once the existence of a mental disorder is ascertained, the court will determine an offender’s degree of culpability which will centre on: (a) the degree to which a mental disorder may affect an offender’s control over his offending impulses; (b) the degree to which an offender’s knowledge of the legal rightness or wrongness of his actions is impeded as a result of the disorder; and (c) the extent to which an offender’s awareness of the moral rightness or wrongness of his offending actions is affected by the disorder.[\[note: 12\]](#Ftn_12)

> (iv)     Based on the above sentencing principles laid down by the courts, it is clear that in determining whether to impose a MTO, the focus is not merely on whether an accused possesses rehabilitative potential. The threshold for imposing MTO may not be met if deterrence and retribution trumps rehabilitation, such as in situations where: (a) the accused retained the capacity for control when committing the offence; (b) the offences were consciously committed; and (c) the accused was able to appreciate the nature and quality of his actions. In my view, the sentencing principles of whether an accused retained the capacity for control, committed the offences consciously and was able to appreciate the nature and quality of his actions are relevant in considering whether an offender should be granted a MTO under s 339 of the CPC.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13)

> (v)     I rejected the _Defence submissions_ that if there was an intention for the aforesaid sentencing principles to be considered as a pre-requisite prior to the imposition of a MTO, it would have been codified in the CPC together with the requirement of having a report provided by an appointed psychiatrist. An inquiry into an offender's rehabilitative potential should not take place in a vacuum with a single-minded focus only on his prospects for rehabilitation and ignoring the presence of other sentencing principles because there is a need to balance the sentencing principle of rehabilitation with the other principles, such as deterrence, retribution, and prevention.[\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14)

> _S 447 PC offence in MAC-905469-2020_

> (vi)     A MTO should not be imposed on the AP for the s 447 PC offence in MAC-905469-2020, because the requirement in s 339(3)(c) of the CPC[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15) is not fulfilled as the AP’s psychiatric condition is not one of the contributing factors for the offence. I _disagreed with the Defence submission_ and agreed with the Prosecution that none of the 4 MTO reports dated 21 May 2021, 10 June 2021, 11 June 2021 and 14 March 2022 submitted by Dr Guo (who had stated that the third report was meant to replace the second report, and the second report should be disregarded[^16]) made a satisfactory conclusion as to whether the AP’s psychiatric condition is one of the contributing factors for his s 447 PC offence in MAC-905469-2020 as shown below:

>> (a)       The first report states that his “index offences were _likely linked_ to his paraphilic disorder”[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17).

>> (b)       The third report states that “with regards to the contributing factors for his index offences, the lack of coping mechanisms for his sexual impulses from his fetishistic disorder was involved in the initiation of the motivation which _is linked_ to his index offences stated in the 1st, 2nd and 3rd charges”[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18).

>> (c)       The fourth report states that “he suffers from Paraphilic Disorders with Fetishistic Disorder and Telephone Scatalogia which were _likely linked_ to the alleged offences”.[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19)

>> (d)       The wording in each of the above MTO reports vacillates between inconsistent and tentative. At no point is there a definitive finding by Dr Guo that the AP’s fetishistic disorder is “one of the contributing factors” for the commission of the s 477 PC offence. Further, the inference from the wording of Dr Guo’s reports ought to be that the conclusions in his reports were unsatisfactory. To use the phrase “likely linked” when Dr Guo could have just made a direct finding that there was a “contributory link” is a glaring omission, made all the more glaring by his refusal to endorse those specific words on the stand. In this regard, I found to be instructive what the High Court had stated[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20) that “…_if a psychiatrist does not state clearly in his MTO report that any psychiatric condition is "one of the contributing factors" of the offending conduct in question (in the language of s 339(3)(c) of the CPC), then as far as the court is concerned it must mean that he has made no such finding. Put another way, if he had been prepared to make such a finding, the natural and reasonable assumption is that he ought to and would have specifically said so…”_

> (vii)     While Dr Guo had stated that he used “linked” in an interchangeable way as “contributing factor”,[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21) he subsequently confirmed on numerous occasions that there was _no contributory link_ between the AP’s fetishistic disorder and the s 447 PC offence of criminal trespass, even when asked directly on this issue. No fetishistic impulses operating on him?</em></p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Dr Guo</b>: <em>No</em>, it’s just the, uh, kind of, uh, uh---</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>DPP</b>: Regret?</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Dr Guo</b>: Regret, yah.</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>DPP</b>: <em>So, he was labouring under his regret and he wanted to return?</em></p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Dr Guo</b>: Yes</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="b" colspan="2" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Summary</b>: Dr Guo confirmed that the s 447 PC offence (3<sup>rd</sup> charge) <em>came about because of the s 380PC and s 3 POHA offences</em>, 1<sup>st</sup> and 2nd charges) and that the fetishistic disorder was a <em>chronological</em> (rather than a <em>contributing</em>) factor as there was <em>no loss of autonomy</em>.</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">NEs, 23 Mar 2022, Day 3 – Page 49, lines 10 to 16; Page 50, lines 11 to 26</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>DC</b>: The 3rd charge, when he felt remorse and to return.</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Dr Guo</b>: Yah.</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>DC</b>: That came from the first 2 charge, the action---</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Dr Guo</b>: Yah.</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>DC</b>: to return. > (viii)    It appears clear from the above Dr Guo’s evidence that his sole instance of affirming that the AP’s psychiatric disorder was a contributory factor to the criminal trespass charge was made in the context of affirming that it was a chronological, rather than causal or contributory factor. The _focus of the Defence questions_ was not whether the AP was in fact affected by any mental disorder, but rather, saying that the remorse from the 3rd charge “came from the first 2 charge, the action to return”. The context of Dr Guo’s remarks was that the 3rd charge “came from” the AP’s psychiatric disorder, in the sense that the disorder caused the AP to commit the offences that are the subject of the first two charges, and are thus part of a sequence of events that led to the AP trespassing to return the vibrator.

> (ix)     A “contributing factor” in s 339(3)(c) of the CPC cannot be a mere part of the chain of events that leads to the AP’s commission of an offence as the language of s 339(3)(c) of the CPC states that “the psychiatric condition” must be one of the “contributing factors” for the AP committing the offence, which plainly means that the fetishistic disorder itself must have contributed to or caused the AP to conduct himself in a certain manner in respect of the offence. This interpretation is supported by the Second Reading speech, where the Minister for Law, Mr K Shanmugam, stated that one of the conditions for the imposition of MTO was that the accused’s “psychiatric condition had contributed to the commission of the offence”[\[note: 22\]](#Ftn_22). There is nothing in the text and context of the provision, or the secondary materials, which supports the proposition that it would suffice for the psychiatric condition to be part of a chronology of events leading up to the commission of the offence. As such, it will not suffice if the fetishistic disorder contributed to other offences and the present offence incidentally occurred after the other offences. In this regard, _I rejected the Defence submission_ that there is nothing in s 339 of the CPC that precludes contributing links based on chronological factors and that even if the link is chronological, it is still a contributing factor, whereby the s 447 offence would not have occurred but for the AP's fetishistic disorder.

> (x)     For the aforesaid reasons, the AP’s fetishistic disorder was not one of the contributing factors for the commission of the s 477 PC offence and this Court is precluded from imposing a MTO, given Dr Guo’s confirmation that: (a) he meant contributory link in the sense of an indirect link; (b) the AP’s main motivation was “regret”; (c) there was no fetishistic impulse operating on him at the time of the offence; and (d) “contributing factor” meant merely as part of a sequence of events that led to the AP returning vibrator, rather than his fetishistic impulses actively operating on him at the material time.

> (xi)     I agreed with the Prosecution that _the Defence submissions_ that the AP’s fetishistic disorder can still be a contributing factor to the s 447 PC offence, even if it was indirect and was not operating on the AP at the time of the offence, as long as there is some semblance of ‘but-for’ causation between any impulse arising from the fetishistic disorder is untenable because:

>> (a)       Dr Guo’s use of the word “indirect” is no accident of wording. He repeatedly denied any direct link, and confirmed in court that the main impulse leading the AP to trespass into the victim’s room was regret. Dr Guo was asked three separate times whether fetishism was one of the contributing factors for the AP entering the room to return the vibrator. All three times, Dr Guo replied that it was “not directly linked”. If Dr Guo had believed that an indirect link did indeed mean the same thing as a contributing factor, he could have easily clarified this, or simply affirmed the question. Instead, his reluctance to answer the question suggests that he viewed an ‘indirect link’ as not being the same as a “contributing factor”.

>> (b)       It is plainly wrong to treat ‘but-for causation’ as equivalent to being a ‘contributing factor’ under s 339(3)(c) CPC. But-for causation alone cannot be sufficient. This would be untenable as a general principle, because it would suggest that any act the AP did as a result of finding himself in possession of the vibrator (be it causing property damage with the vibrator, or using it to hit someone else) would automatically be contributorily linked with the AP’s fetishistic disorder, no matter the circumstances of the subsequent act. Clearly, once the AP’s fetishistic order ceased to be operative on him, as Dr Guo has admitted in relation to the returning of the vibrator, how he happened to come into possession of that vibrator should be irrelevant for the purposes of s 339(3)(c) CPC. The correct and reasonable interpretation would be that a psychiatric disorder would be contributorily linked to an offence only if it was operating on him at the relevant time of the offence, by causing or contributing to him acting in a particular manner.

>> (c)       The but-for causation alone is insufficient given Dr Guo’s failure to affirm that the AP’s fetishistic disorder had a contributory link to the s 477 PC offence. The court in _GCX (at \[79\]-\[80\])_ noted that the legislative scheme of s 339 CPC primarily looks at whether the appointed psychiatrist is satisfied that the psychiatric condition of the offender was “one of the contributing factors” for the offender having committed the offence, rather than the existence of any “but for” causal link. It is not at all clear that Dr Guo was satisfied of this in the present case.

> (xii)     Based on Dr Guo’s testimony that impulsivity can be a symptom of disorders that are not classified as impulse control disorders (“ICDs”), such as the AP’s fetishistic disorder, and the extent of this impulsivity could be as or more significant than that in ICDs, depending on what happened to the patient at that moment and which would determine how severe the impulse was, I agreed with the Prosecution that the conclusion that _the Defence_ sought to draw from Dr Guo’s aforesaid testimony goes beyond what Dr Guo mentioned. _The Defence_ argued that “while impulsivity is not a feature of a disorder, it does not negate the fact that patients would still experience impulsivity as a symptom, and therefore be subject to the same irresistible urges because of the disorder”. This suggests that people with fetishistic disorder will necessarily experience impulsivity, which is an overstatement of Dr Guo’s point that it is possible for symptoms of impulsivity to be present. The same applies to the extent of impulsivity – just because impulsivity caused by fetishistic disorders has the potential to be irresistible like in ICDs does not mean every impulse arising from a fetishistic disorder is necessarily irresistible. As pointed out by the Prosecution, a holistic consideration of the AP ’s behaviour will show that much of the preparatory conduct for the AP to commit the relevant offences was done when the AP was experiencing impulses that were resistible.

> (xiii)     _Contrary to the Defence submissions_ that Dr Guo agreed that punishment will not aid rehabilitation if the patient is already compliant with treatment and the AP was labouring under irresistible impulses when committing each of the offences, I accepted the Prosecution submissions that :

>> (a)       the custodial sentence sought will not be a barrier to the AP seeking treatment, due to the relatively short duration (4 weeks). This was confirmed by Dr Guo[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23), although when questioned during the hearing, whether in his professional opinion, an offender suffering from fetishistic disorder can be deterred through treatment and punishment, Dr Guo stated that he does not agree as "punishment won 't change the behaviour.”[^24]

>> (b)       while Dr Guo takes the position that punishment (e.g. imprisonment) is more suitable for a person who is non-compliant with treatment, and that treatment should continue for a person who is compliant, this does not mean that a compliant person cannot be deterred by punishment. The fact that Dr Guo concedes that a person who is non-compliant with treatment “can be deterred by punishment” points towards the fact that a compliant person would likewise be deterred by punishment. It would be illogical if only non-compliant persons can be deterred by punishment but not so for compliant persons, since both categories of accused persons would be suffering from the same disorder.

>> (c)       in any event, the question of whether to impose MTO hinges on whether rehabilitation outweighs deterrence and retribution, and Dr Guo’s view that a compliant person should continue with treatment is not determinative of the eventual punishment that this court should impose since this court and not Dr Guo is tasked with balancing the competing sentencing principles.

>> (d)       a holistic consideration of the AP’s actions would show that that he possessed deliberation and premeditation, and committed substantial preparatory acts whilst any impulses that he had were still resistible.

>> (e)       Dr Guo’s testimony shows that up to the point where the offences were acted out, the AP retained his capacity to make intentional choices. As pointed out by the Defence, Dr Guo believes that the AP lost his control over his sexual drive “at the point that…the person acting out”, indicating that the loss of control happened at the moment of the offence itself. That the AP’s impulses were resistible until the moment of the offences is also shown by Dr Guo’s testimony that the AP’s impulsivity builds up over a period of time. It should be noted that the offences in question were not just short term opportunism, but involved some level of planning and goal-directedness, for example, in locating the victim’s room.

> (xiv)     The evidence also evinced that the offences were not committed by the AP acting on uncontrollable impulses as follows:

>> (a)       In relation to the s 380 PC offence, Dr Guo testified that even though the AP was labouring under his fetishistic impulses, he retained the ability to decide not to steal. Dr Guo also confirmed that the AP’s actions were goal directed and he knew that his conduct was wrong.

>> (b)       In relation to the s 447 PC offence, apart from the fact that he was not labouring under any fetishistic disorder at the time of offence, Dr Guo also testified that right before the offence, even at the doorway to the victim’s room, the AP was able to exercise control over himself and there was no impulsivity involved before entering the room[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25). Even prior to arriving at the door, the SOF (at \[11\]) makes it clear that the AP’s actions were premeditated and deliberate as only after he saw the victim’s Instastory which showed that she would not be in her hostel room did he decide to trespass into her room, and he had the presence of mind to closely follow behind another student with access to the hostel before making the calculated decision to enter the room as he knew that the victim was not present.

>> (c)       In relation to the s 3 POHA offence, Dr Guo testified that the AP would be able to resist the impulse to take out his phone to message the victim, and that the impulse to search for the victim’s name was also resistible to some extent at the beginning[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26).

> (xv)     In _PP v Kong Keng Yee_ _<span class="citation">\[2018\] 2 SLR 295</span>_ where the offender had late onset psychosis with persecutory, jealous and nihilistic/somatic delusions, and he experienced a brief psychotic episode at the time of the offence which substantially impaired his mental responsibility for his actions, as well as “exhibited incoherent and irrational behaviour before, during and after the offence” and his decisions were “premised on totally unreal facts and completely irrational thoughts…\[which\] emanated from an impaired mind”, the Court of Appeal stated (_at \[64\]–\[66\])_ as follows:

>> “64    The Prosecution maintains that the Respondent “retained full control of his actions” and could have controlled his impulse to kill the Deceased at the time of the offence. It has been said that a mental disorder which vitiates the offender’s self-control is ordinarily mitigating (see Chong Hou En (\[59\] supra) at \[33\]). Thus in Chong Yee Ka v PP <span class="citation">\[2017\] 4 SLR 309</span> at \[82\], where the offender was diagnosed with obsessive compulsive disorder and depressive disorder, the crucial issue was “whether the disorder(s) … contributed so significantly to the offending conduct that it diminishe\[d\] the offender’s capacity to exercise self-control and restraint” (cited by this court in PP v BDB <span class="citation">\[2018\] 1 SLR 127</span> at \[106\]). **Self-control is only one aspect of the overall consideration. The essence of a brief psychotic episode is that it warps the individual’s sense of reality**. Although the Respondent might have known how or even when to kill the Deceased, his mind was truly in an unreal world in which he had to kill or be killed. The underlying factual basis for him to think or to feel the way he felt before and during the offence was totally irrational and was not just the working of an overly suspicious or jealous mind. It is the equivalent of seeing a person seeking to embrace him as one trying to engulf and suffocate him or a delusional architect planning a beautiful mansion on imaginary rocks. The Respondent’s delusion altered his appreciation of his actions significantly.

>> 65    The psychosis which plagued the Respondent also served to distinguish this case from many of the precedents cited to us. **The moral culpability of mentally disordered offenders lies on a spectrum. On the one hand there are offenders who have temporary and situational mental disorders who retain their understanding of their actions and can reason and weigh the consequences. Such offenders often evince the ability to think logically and coherently, borne out by a sophisticated degree of planning and premeditation.** The important distinction between such cases and the Respondent’s situation is this. Invariably, **the factual basis for such offenders’ actions is a true and rational one**, unlike the Respondent’s case. For instance, it could be severe depression caused by intense jealousy and anger over an unfaithful spouse who is in fact in an extra-marital relationship with another person. It could also be depression due to worry and fear that the offender’s employer has found out about the offender’s wrongdoing and is about to terminate the employment or to take disciplinary action against him. In such cases, the underlying reason for the offender’s subsequent criminal conduct is founded on fact, not fantasy or fiction. Hence, in such cases, the mental disorder invariably dissipates or disappears altogether once the underlying situation is removed (for instance by killing the unfaithful spouse or the third party or by killing the employer) and there is no need for psychotic medication or follow-up medical attention. **The mental disorder in such cases can only ameliorate to a limited extent the criminal conduct because the offender’s mind is still rational. In such cases, deterrence and retribution should still feature because depression, even if severe, cannot be a licence to kill or to harm others.**

>> 66    On the other hand, there are offenders whose mental disorders impair severely their ability to understand the nature and consequences of their acts, to make reasoned decisions or to control their impulses. The Respondent’s brief psychotic episode was in this category. He exhibited incoherent and irrational behaviour before, during and after the offence. He muttered incoherently to people he did not know. He stabbed and slashed unrelentingly at an elderly, defenceless woman with two dangerous weapons. Whatever seemingly rational decisions that he made were premised on totally unreal facts and completely irrational thoughts. His actions were not merely a maladaptive response to a difficult or depressive true situation, such as a temporary loss of self-control. Instead, they emanated from an impaired mind.” (emphasis mine)

> (xvi)     I _disagreed with the Defence submissions_ that it would suffice if it can be shown that the individual's sense of reality was warped, that his mind was in an unreal world, that the way he thought was totally irrational and that this delusion had significantly altered his appreciation of his actions significantly. I accepted the Prosecution submissions that the AP was plainly suffering from a significantly less serious disorder than the offender in _Kong Peng Yee_, and there was no evidence that the AP’s actions were "irrational, with a warped sense of reality. On the contrary, his conduct before, during and after the first three offences showed that the offences were the product of a rational mind, as he was able to plan the offences, take preparatory steps to ensure that the victim was not home, carry out the offences with deliberation, and express regret after committing them, as he knew that his actions were wrong. As for the s3 POHA offence, there was likewise no warped sense of reality - he knew who the victim was, he knew that what he was doing was wrong, and he appreciated the nature of what he was doing (sending lewd messages), which corresponded to reality. Compared to the high threshold the Court of Appeal had in mind in _Kong Peng Yee (at \[66\])_, the AP's actions cannot by any measure be described to be founded on "totally unreal facts and completely irrational thoughts". Applying _Kong Peng Yee at \[65\]_, the AP's culpability would be on the higher end of the spectrum, warranting the applicability of deterrence and retribution, as his mental disorder can only ameliorate to a limited extent and cannot be a licence to harm others.

> (xvii)    Even if fetishistic impulses were operating on the AP at some points during the s 380 PC offence and the s 3 POHA offence, it should be noted that the AP, while still in control of his actions, committed substantial preparatory acts towards the commission of these offences, as well as the s 447 PC offence, and intentionally placed himself in positions which would have increased the extent of his impulses. Further, these offences were consciously committed, and he understood the nature and wrongfulness of his actions, but nonetheless acted in a goal-directed manner to satisfy his sexual preferences. Any consideration of the AP’s culpability must thus factor in the choices he made while the impulse was still building up, rather than just the immediate moment of the offence itself. Given that the AP acted with deliberation and consciously placed himself in positions which made him prone to giving in to his fetishistic impulses, I agreed with the Prosecution that his offences were the result of a rational mind, and deterrence and retribution should thus feature prominently over rehabilitation. Accordingly, the mere fact that he possesses rehabilitative potential does not tilt the balance in favour of rehabilitation being the dominant consideration.

> (xviii)     _In this regard, I rejected the Defence submissions_ that “an indirect link is still a link” and it would suffice for Dr Guo to simply conclude that the disorder was a contributing factor towards the commission of the s477 PC offence, and this was what Dr Guo had done, albeit he had found the contributing factor to be an indirect one, bearing in mind what the High Court had stated (in _PP v Low Gek Hong_ _<span class="citation">\[2015\] SGDC 192</span> at \[13\])_ that an indirect link was "a qualified characterisation which falls short of the requirement specified in s 339(3)(c) of the CPC which makes no mention of "indirect contributory factors".

> _S 380 PC offence in DAC-913108-2020_

> (xix)     It would not be expedient to impose a MTO in respect of the s 380 PC offence in in DAC-913108-2020 as general and specific deterrence overrides rehabilitation, given that the offence was committed consciously, and the AP’s condition did not detract from his ability to appreciate the wrongfulness of his conduct. Specific deterrence is a key sentencing consideration where there is a conscious choice to commit crimes[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27). The existence of a mental disorder does not nullify the applicability of specific deterrence where there is a “_conscious choice_ to commit the offence”, and where the disorder did not seriously inhibit the offender’s ability to “appreciate the nature and quality of his actions.”[^28] In the same vein, general deterrence remains relevant given that offenders who consciously commit offences and are not labouring under uncontrollable impulses can be deterred[^29].

> (xx)      _Contrary to the Defence submissions_ that the AP’s fetishistic disorder had directly contributed to the offence and that it is not unprecedented for an offender who had committed theft under the influence of fetishistic disorder to be granted a MTO[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30), I agreed with the Prosecution that the above sentencing principles should apply with full force to the s 380 PC offence in DAC-913108-2020 as each case must be decided based on its own facts which _the Defence_ also agreed. While it is undisputed that the AP suffered from fetishistic disorder, this was not a case of an individual acting on uncontrollable impulses. Dr Guo confirmed that the AP was goal-directed in stealing the vibrator to satisfy his abnormal sexual drive, and that even if the AP was labouring under some fetishistic impulses, he retained the ability to decide not to steal. Dr Guo also confirmed that the AP acted consciously, and he knew that his actions were legally and morally wrong, which explained why he regretted stealing the vibrator. Given these concessions by Dr Guo, general and specific deterrence remain relevant and important considerations over rehabilitation in the present case. So, that’s why he also regretted after that.</em></p></td></tr></tbody></table>

  
  

> _S 3 POHA offence in MAC-905470-2020_

> (xxi)     It would not be expedient to impose a MTO in respect of the s 3 POHA offence in MAC-905470-2020. While Dr Guo stated that telephone scatalogia was a contributing factor to the AP committing the POHA offence, a MTO should not be imposed as deterrence and retribution should be accorded greater weight over rehabilitation, given that the AP acted consciously and his telephone scatalogia did not seriously impair his ability to appreciate the nature and gravity of his actions. Deterrence must override rehabilitation as the AP acted consciously. The AP demonstrated his ability to act consciously with deliberation, goal-directness, and he was able to appreciate the wrongful and illegal nature of his conduct. This is evident from the following aspects:

>> (a)       In the SOF at \[15\], the AP admitted that he felt sexually aroused thinking about how he had entered the victim’s room and looked through her belongings, and thus made the decision to message the victim on Telegram via a secret chat. In order to do so, he had to take active and concerted steps to find the victim on Telegram by searching for her Instagram handle (the same handle she used on Telegram). He deliberately chose to remain anonymous by employing a pseudonymous username ‘Bobby’, while hiding his phone number and personal details on Telegram.

>> (b)       Dr Guo confirmed that the AP retained _the ability to fight his impulses to some extent and to refrain from messaging the victim before he took out his phone_. This showed that at least at the _initial stages of the offence_, he could have _prevented himself from committing the offence_, but he did not refrain from doing so. Instead, he allowed himself to embark on a series of actions which led to him sending the insulting messages to the victim. Relevant extracts of the NEs are reproduced below:

>> (c)       Dr Guo confirmed that although the AP had telephone scatalogia, he committed the offence _consciously_, with _goal-directness_, and _appreciated the wrongful nature of his conduct._ Relevant extracts of the NEs are reproduced below:

> (xxii)    The specific messages sent by the AP showed a calculated manipulativeness and strategized deception as follows:

>> (a)       “Take your time to digest this piece of news” – the messages were not just about wanting a sexual relationship, but acknowledging that the AP was in possession of private information that left the victim in alarm, fear and confusion of how he obtained it; and

>> (b)       “I’m the only one you can talk to about this” – isolating the victim and making her less inclined to tell others and report his actions.

> (xxiii)    In _Low Ji Qing_ at \[47\] – \[48\], the offender who was diagnosed with fetishism and the IMH psychiatrist described his actions as “goal directed” and aimed at satisfying a desire, notwithstanding the offender’s mental condition, Chief Justice Sundaresh Menon (“**Menon CJ**”) instructively stated that “_specific deterrence remained a key sentencing principle_”, given that the offender’s “_cognisance and control remained sufficiently intact_”. In the present case, given that Dr Guo likewise confirmed that the AP acted “consciously” to remain anonymous, and also acted with goal directedness to fulfil his need for the abnormal sexual preference, this showed that his cognisance and control remained intact, and specific deterrence remains an overriding consideration over rehabilitation.

> (xxiv)    Retribution must take precedence over rehabilitation as the AP appreciated the nature and gravity of his conduct in the present case. The nature of the s 3 POHA offence attracts the applicability of retribution. The retributive principle requires the punishment to “reflect and befit the seriousness of the crime”[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31). Retribution may prevail over rehabilitation, even in situations where an offender is suffering from a mental disorder and if an offender acts with knowledge of what he is doing and of the gravity of his actions, and the offence is particularly serious or heinous, the principles of deterrence, retribution and protection may assume primacy in the sentencing process[^32]. In assessing the culpability of a mentally disordered offender, apart from considering the degree to which a mental disorder may affect an offender’s control over his offending impulses, regard should also be given to the issue of whether the offender’s awareness of the legal and moral wrongness was impeded by the mental disorder[^33]. A custodial sentence should not be lightly or readily imposed, “unless the nature of the offence justifies its imposition retributively or _as a general or specific deterrent, where deterrence is called for”[^34]._

> (xxv)     In the present case, the evidence as set out above demonstrates that the AP knew and appreciated that his actions were wrong and his telephone scatalogia did not impair his capacity to appreciate the nature and gravity of his actions. In this regard, _I rejected the Defence submission_ that..” despite not having planned to send the insulting messages, there was some degree of planning as \[the AP\] was under the influence of telephone scatologia and was enhancing his arousal by attempting to remain anonymous. Additionally, there were no disturbances around that could allow him to control his impulses at the starting point, and this eventually resulted in him succumbing to his impulses, thereby committing the 4th offence.” In my view, coupled with the fact that the victim was “alarmed” and “felt very scared” by his actions, retribution must assume primacy over rehabilitation even if, _as submitted by the Defence_, the AP’s telephone scatologia as one of the contributing factors led him to send the 56 anonymous messages to the victim as he had lost his autonomy and was unable to control himself from doing so.

> (xxvi)    In short, a holistic consideration of the present case points away from MTO being expedient. The general pattern of the AP’s conduct shows deliberation, premeditation, planning, and goal-directedness. Based on the _GCX case_, this points towards deterrence and retribution taking precedence over rehabilitation. Such premeditation is also an indicator of the AP’s culpability and deterrability[\[note: 35\]](#Ftn_35). The nature and circumstances of the AP’s offences wee relatively serious. In relation to the s 447 PC offences for trespass, there was a high degree of intrusion and invasion of privacy. The s380 PC offence of theft of the vibrator involved a private and intimate object. The s 3 POHA offence involved the AP using the private information he obtained from invading the victim’s personal space to place her in a state of fear.

> (xxvii)    For the s 447 PC offence of criminal trespass in MAC-905468-2020 which was taken into consideration, the AP retained control over his offending impulses. Dr Guo confirmed that the AP “retained cognitive control” when he decided to check the victim’s Instagram to find out where she lived and when making his way to the campus[\[note: 36\]](#Ftn_36). Dr Guo also affirmed that the AP retained the conscious choice not to tailgate his way into the controlled access entry of the hostel, could fight his impulses to not walk along the corridor to her room, and could fight the impulse not to enter the room, but he chose to do so anyway[^37].

> (xxviii)    As for the s 380 PC offence in DAC-913108-2020, the act of stealing the vibrator should be viewed in the broader context of the criminal trespass into the victim’s room and the theft was the cumulative result of the intentional preparatory steps taken by the AP. The s 447 offence of criminal trespass in MAC-905469-2020 was not a once-off offence, as the AP re-entered the victim’s room again with intent to annoy, while not labouring under any fetishistic impulses. As for the s 3 POHA offence in MAC-905470-2020, Dr Guo had confirmed that he was able to fight his impulses to some degree at the start.

> (xxix)    Hence, it was clear that the 4 offences were not opportunistically committed by the AP, but were the result of conscious and deliberate actions on his part. Given the nature of the offences where he intruded into the victim’s property twice, stole an intimate item, and coupled with the fact that his actions escalated to sending the victim messages when he had the ability to control his impulses at the start, and considering the alarm and fear caused to the victim, the compelling considerations of deterrence and retribution must override rehabilitation in the present case.

> (xxx)     I agreed with the Prosecution that _the mitigating factors as advanced by the Defence_ are not sufficient to warrant a MTO or a non-custodial sentence for reasons as follows:

>> (a)        _The Defence submission_ that the present case is "not as serious as other sexual related offences" is hardly mitigating as the AP is not being charged for other sexual offences, and if so, the sentences may well be higher.

>> (b)       The AP's remorse, cooperation with authorities, willingness to seek treatment, apology, and guilty plea are mitigating factors which in themselves do not warrant a non-custodial sentence based on the facts and circumstances of the present offences. Further, the victim has not accepted the AP's apology, as she was unable to accept the fact that he had entered her room and took her private item without her knowledge.

>> (c)        _The Defence submissions_ that the value of the stolen vibrator was low and that it has been returned, and that "full restitution may substantially reduce the economic harm suffered by the victim[\[note: 38\]](#Ftn_38)" should not be given much weight because the gravitas of the theft offence lies not just in the financial value of the vibrator, but in the loss of a personal and intimate item, which the victim assumed was in the privacy of her own room. That the vibrator’s private nature was important to the victim was shown by how the AP subsequently used his knowledge of the item to psychologically scare the victim in the s 3 POHA offence by making reference to her ‘dirty little secret’. Further, trespassing into the victim's room for a second time to put a stolen vibrator anonymously back in the drawer is not equivalent to offering genuine restitution to the victim in an open court setting. Any genuine remorse could have been shown by not harassing the victim any further, rather than committing a further breach of privacy by trespassing into her room again. Given that the AP had used the stolen vibrator to facilitate his masturbation, the fact that the used item was "returned" to her would only offer cold comfort. Moreover, given that the impact of the victim's loss was not just financial, restitution of the economic harm alone should not be given significant weight.

>> (d)       Limited weight should be placed on the AP's lack of antecedents, as he faces numerous offences committed over separate occasions, and cannot be considered a true first offender[\[note: 39\]](#Ftn_39).

> (xxxi)     _For the above reasons, I was not able to accept the Defence submissions_ that the imposition of a MTO in the present case would be appropriate, given the circumstances of the present case, as well as the AP 's mitigating factors and high rehabilitative potential_._ While Dr Guo is an experienced psychiatrist with 17 years of experience[\[note: 40\]](#Ftn_40) who had recommended a MTO for the AP in his MTO reports as the AP is susceptible to treatment, it must be borne in mind that Dr Guo’s report would be considered "final and conclusive" under s 339(9) CPC if and only his MTO reports had fulfilled all the conditions as set out in s 339(3) CPC and it is also the duty of this Court to consider and determine whether the threshold for granting a MTO had been met in the present case as the sentencing principles of deterrence and retribution trump rehabilitation for the s 380 PC and s 3 POHA offences since the AP retained the capacity for control when committing the offences; the offences were consciously committed; and the AP was able to appreciate the nature and quality of his actions, _although his mental condition was a significant contributing factor to the commission of the offences and he can be treated, as submitted by the Defence._ Further, the requirement in s 339(3)(c) of the CPC is not fulfilled for the s 447 PC offence as the AP’s psychiatric condition is not one of the contributing factors for the offence and Dr Guo’s finding of an indirect contributing factor for the offence does not satisfy the aforesaid requirement. In this regard, I note the alternative Defence submission for a short custodial sentence to be imposed for the s 447 PC offence since there is only an indirect link to the AP’s psychiatric condition.

##### ISSUE (II)(A) TO (II)(C)

9       As I agreed with the Prosecution that the compelling considerations of deterrence and retribution must override rehabilitation for the s 380 PC and s 3 POHA offences and that the requirement in s 339(3)(c) of the CPC that the AP’s psychiatric condition must be one of the contributing factors is not fulfilled for the s 447 PC offence, a custodial sentence must be imposed on the AP in respect of each of the proceeded charges. Accordingly, I sentenced the AP for each of the proceeded charges as follows.

#### Sentence for the s 447 PC offence in MAC-905469-2020

10     I accepted the Prosecution’s submissions for a sentence of at least 3 weeks’ imprisonment for the s 447 PC offence in MAC-905469-2020 for the following reasons:

> (i)     The relevant considerations for an offence of criminal trespass (_Sentencing Practice in the Subordinate Courts_ (3rd Ed, LexisNexis, 2013) at pp 909 and 911) are set out below:

>> Criminal trespass can be committed with a variety of intents, and the nature of intent is a relevant factor in sentence. For example, criminal trespass with intent to commit an offence will be regarded more severely than criminal trespass with intent to annoy. The other considerations for assessing sentence would be the nature of the property trespassed upon, the circumstances attending the trespass and the criminal record, if relevant.

![](data:image;base64,)

> (ii)     The custodial threshold has been crossed in the present case for the reasons below:

>> (a)        _Premeditation and planning_: There was significant premeditation, deliberation and planning which are well-established aggravating factors[\[note: 41\]](#Ftn_41). This is evident from the SOF at \[11\]-\[12\] which shows that: the AP first checked the victim’s Instastory to ensure that she was not at her hostel; he decided to trespass into her room with intent to annoy her after finding out that she was not in her room; and he made his way to her hostel by carefully tailgating a student.

>> (b)        _Nature of the property trespassed upon_: The AP trespassed upon private property belonging to a victim of the opposite sex. The fact that he “regretted” his actions is no excuse for him to enter the room again. Not only did he enter her room, he went further to take a photo of her resume and even masturbated in her room.

>> (c)        _Second s 447 PC offence and TIC charge_: This was the second occasion of trespass, and it is well-established that a TIC charge enhances the sentence imposed[\[note: 42\]](#Ftn_42).

>> (d)        _Not labouring under fetishistic impulses_: As stated above, the AP was not labouring under any fetishistic impulses for the s 447 PC offence and there is no reason why leniency ought to be accorded to him.

> (c)     While I agreed with _the Defence submission_ that the sentencing precedents (set out below) as relied upon by the Prosecution did not involve any mental disorder, I am mindful that no two cases can or will ever be completely identical or symmetrical as sentencing is neither a science nor an administrative exercise and sentences cannot be determined with mathematical certainty nor should they be arbitrary, but the sentence must fit the crime.[\[note: 43\]](#Ftn_43) I accepted the Prosecution’s submissions and calibration of the cases below which I found to be analogous and instructive. **At least 3 weeks’ imprisonment** is consistent with the cases below. The first case below shows that the imposition of a stiff custodial sentence is necessary to deter trespassers seeking to take advantage of young students in hostels:

#### Sentence for the s 380 PC offence in DAC-913108-2020

11     I agreed with the Prosecution that 5 days’ imprisonment is appropriate for the s 380 PC offence in DAC-913108-2020 for the reasons as follows:

> (i)     For property offences, while the economic value of a property is an important consideration, economic value per se does not reflect other forms of “intangible harm”, which should be factored into sentencing[\[note: 44\]](#Ftn_44).

> (ii)     The aggravating factors to be taken into account for this offence are as follows:

>> (a)       The AP deliberately trespassed into the victim’s room with the intention of finding her private items (initially her swimsuit, subsequently her vibrator), invading a deeply personal space; and

>> (b)       While the value of the vibrator was not high, the gravitas of the offence is that a very personal and private item was stolen from the victim’s private residence. There is significant potential harm, as the loss of the item can cause great embarrassment, especially if there is disclosure of the victim’s identity, which can result in harm to her reputation and privacy. Further, harm did materialise, as the AP made use of his knowledge of her owning the vibrator to his advantage in respect of the s3 POHA charge.

> (iii)     Viewed in the above light, I rejected _the following Defence submissions that_ :

>> (a)       “..the current case is one that is unique as although it involves a theft of a personal item, it was not in the same category as cases involving outrage and/or insult of modesty”;

>> (b)       ”… there was no direct contact between \[the AP\] and the victim, and therefore arguably less intrusive than other cases.”; and

>> (c)       “…the value of the item stolen is relatively low ($40), and the item was eventually returned to the owner, albeit in a wrong manner. As such, …there was no economic loss suffered by the victim. It bears emphasis that \[the AP\] had not stolen the vibrator for any monetary benefit—he had done so under the influence of his fetishistic disorder…. , full restitution may substantially reduce the economic harm suffered by the victim”[\[note: 45\]](#Ftn_45).

> (iv)     The mitigating factors to be taken into account for this offence are that the AP who was a first offender had pleaded guilty, and suffered from fetishistic disorder (although as explained above, he retained the ability to control his impulses), and _as submitted by the Defence, he had also written a letter of apology to the victim to demonstrate his genuine remorse and contrition in mitigation_[\[note: 46\]](#Ftn_46), but the victim had refused to accept the apology as she was unable to accept the fact that he had entered her room and took her private item without her knowledge.

> (v)     I note that the sentencing precedents of _PP v Pei Shao Bo__[\[note: 47\]](#Ftn_47) and Lee Chee Kin v PP[^48]_ cited by the Prosecution as well as that of _PP v Wu Jack Long, Thomas[^49]_ were unreported cases for which I had to bear in mind what the High Court in _Luong Thi Trang Hoang Kathleen v PP <span class="citation">\[2010\] 1 SLR 707</span>_ had cautioned against relying on unreported decisions indiscriminately in determining the appropriate sentence for a particular case before the court since the detailed facts and circumstances of these cases were hardly disclosed or documented with sufficient clarity to enable any intelligent comparison to be made, and comparisons based on unreported decisions are difficult and are likely to be misleading because a proper appraisal of the particular facts and circumstances is simply lacking. While I agreed with _the Defence submission_ that the case of _PP v GED <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGDC 6</span>_ (set out below) as relied upon by the Prosecution did not involve any mental disorder, no two cases can or will ever be completely identical or symmetrical.[^50] I accepted the Prosecution’s calibration of the case below and found it to be analogous and instructive as follows:

#### Sentence for the s 3 POHA offence in MAC-905470-2020

12     I accepted the Prosecution submission that at least 1 week’s imprisonment is appropriate for the s 3 POHA offence in MAC-905470-2020 for the reasons as follows:

> (i)     The custodial threshold is crossed in our case, given the culpability and the harm involved:

>> (a)        _Distressing and manipulative nature of the messages_: While there were no graphic or compromising photos involved, the messages were sexually explicit and disturbing. The AP claimed to know the victim’s “dirty little secret” that she had a “magic wand vibrator” – information that he only would have known as he had been in her room and found the item. He attempted to manipulate the victim by stating that “I’m the only one you can talk to about this”, seeking to take advantage of her vulnerable and fearful state to isolate her into not disclosing the incident to others.

>> (b)        _Significant harm caused_: The messages caused a significant degree of distress to the victim since it leveraged on private information that would have made her fearful of her safety and privacy. The AP knew that the information would shock her, since he told her to “_take your time to digest this piece of news_”. The victim’s distress is further exacerbated by the AP hiding behind a veil of anonymity, which would have put her in greater fear. Indeed, as stated in the SOF at \[17\], apart from feeling alarmed, she felt “very scared”.

>> (c)        _Ability to fight impulses and some planning_: Dr Guo confirmed that the AP retained the ability to fight his impulses to some extent to refrain from messaging the victim before he took out his phone. Yet, he allowed himself to embark on the step of taking out his phone to message her, which resulted in him committing the offence. There was some element of planning involved, as he had the presence of mind to look for her on Telegram, use a secret chat, and remain anonymous.

>> (d)        _Difficulty of detection_: The offence is extremely difficult to detect, given that the AP hid behind the veil of anonymity, and it was purely through the victim’s resourcefulness that resulted in his apprehension. In the SOF at \[18\], the victim scrolled through her Instagram stories and Instagram posts to find the culprit, and eventually found a photograph of a person (i.e., the AP ) who resembled the image of the person who trespassed into her room, as shown on the NUS CCTV footage. Based on checks with a mutual friend of the AP, the victim suspected that the AP was the culprit, and thus provided the details to the Police.

> (ii)     While I agreed with _the Defence submission_ that the sentencing precedents set out below) as relied upon by the Prosecution are clearly distinguishable[\[note: 51\]](#Ftn_51) from our present case, no two cases can or will ever be completely identical or symmetrical[^52]. I accepted the Prosecution’s calibration of the sentencing precedents below which I found to be analogous and instructive and supported a sentence of at least 1 week’s imprisonment in order to take into account the AP’s culpability and the harm caused to the victim and reflect the gravity of the offences:



#### GLOBAL SENTENCE

13     For all the above reasons, I sentenced the AP to 3 weeks’ imprisonment for the s 447 PC offence in MAC-905469-2020, 5 days’ imprisonment for the s 380 PC offence in DAC-913108-2020 and 1 week’s imprisonment the s 3 POHA offence in MAC-905470-2020. The general rule is that sentences for unrelated offences should run consecutively, as an offender who commits unrelated offences should be punished separately for each offence[\[note: 53\]](#Ftn_53). Technically, all three sentences should run consecutively given that they involved different transactions and invade different legally protected interests. However, considering the totality of the circumstances, the AP’s plea of guilt, and his mental condition, I accepted the Prosecution submission that only the sentences for s 447 PC offence and s 3 POHA offence should run consecutively, with a global sentence of **4 weeks’ imprisonment**.

##### ISSUE (III)

#### Whether a suspended sentence is appropriate

14     I agreed with the Prosecution that a suspended sentence under s 377(6) of the CPC should not be imposed in the present case for the reasons as follows:

> (i)     The learned author in _Beyond Prison – Alternative Sentencing in Singapore_ (Academy Publishing, 2021) at p 210 instructively stated the following:

>> “A suspended imprisonment sentence encourages the offender to comply with the terms of his community sentence. However, it also significantly limits the court’s discretion to determine the appropriate breach sanction if the offender breaches his community sentence or reoffends during his sentence. In such circumstances, the suspended imprisonment term will automatically take effect regardless of the severity of the breach. **It is hence suggested that the suspended imprisonment term is a condition that ought to be reserved for exceptional cases, for instance, where there is a clear risk of non-compliance that needs to be addressed**.” (emphasis mine)

> (ii)     As there is no evidence of a “clear risk of non-compliance” in the present case, it is unnecessary to impose a suspended imprisonment term. This would also better allow the Court to calibrate the breach action (if any) to take into account the severity of the breach.

> (iii)     In this regard, _I rejected the Defence submission_ for this Court to consider imposing a MTO on the AP for the offences under the s 380 PC and s3 POHA offences as they are directly linked to his psychiatric condition, and to impose a suspended sentence for the s 447 PC offence. I note that _the Defence has cited no case authority for its submission_ that the determining point for a suspended sentence under s 377(6) of the CPC is that it must be on exceptional basis and the present case is exceptional or unique because for the s 447 PC offence, the AP’s psychiatric disorder while contributing, is an indirect contributing factor. I found nothing exceptional or unique in the aforesaid reason to justify a suspended sentence under s 377(6) of the CPC. The Defence has also not suggested any term of suspended imprisonment that would be suitable for the three proceeded charges and it is unclear what the suspended imprisonment term would achieve in the present case.

## CONCLUSION

15     In my view, the sentence of 4 weeks’ imprisonment which I have imposed on the AP was not manifestly excessive or inadequate, but wholly appropriate and commensurate with the nature and extent of the AP’s culpability, and was a sufficient deterrent sentence tempered with proportionality without the effect of a crushing sentence. _Contrary to the Defence submissions_, I took the view that even a high or substantial fine will not have a deterrent effect on the AP himself ("specific deterrence"), as well as on others ("general deterrence") in the present case in the light of the sentencing principles and precedents highlighted above.

16     Further, a custodial sentence per se is not a barrier to rehabilitation[\[note: 54\]](#Ftn_54). Neither _the Defence_ nor Dr Guo have suggested any reason why rehabilitation cannot take place concurrently in prison in the present case. Moreover, the global custodial sentence of 4 weeks’ imprisonment (and taking into account one-third remission) is not of a particularly long duration such that it would disrupt the AP’s rehabilitation and deprive him of family support required for his rehabilitation and treatment, as recommended[^55] by Dr Guo for him to undergo mandatory treatment for a duration of one year which may include, but is not limited to, pharmacotherapy, counselling, psychotherapy, or hospitalization when necessary.

In respect of the three proceeded charges, all three victims resided in female-only levels in the Raffles Hall and did not have a habit of locking their doors. The cost of the undergarments stolen on each occasion cost around $30 - $50. The offender was sentenced to 3 weeks’ imprisonment per charge, with a total sentence of 6 weeks’ imprisonment.

[^48]: where the offender trespassed into various residential properties to commit theft of female undergarments. He would climb over the back gate of the target unit and enter the laundry area / backyard area where bras and panties were hanging and steal them. He would then leave the premises the way he entered. He used the stolen bras and panties for his sexual gratification. He was diagnosed with fetishistic sexual interest which did not amount to a disorder. He was sentenced as follows: (i) Theft of undergarments worth $60 and $159: 2 weeks’ imprisonment; (ii) Theft of undergarments worth $1,000: 4 weeks’ imprisonment; (iii) s447 trespass charges ranged from 4 to 6 weeks’ imprisonment, with a total sentence of 23 weeks’ imprisonment.

[^49]: where the offender (untraced) faced two proceeded charges under s 380 PC, with ten charges similar taken into consideration. In respect of the two proceeded charges, the offender was a drum teacher, and he stole a total of $260 on two separate occasions when he was at the victim’s house to teach her son. Full restitution was made. He was diagnosed with Persistent Depressive Disorder with a contributory link to the offences. I agreed with the Prosecution that this case is clearly distinguishable on numerous grounds as follows:(a)There was much less premeditation involved as the offender in that case was frequently present at the victim’s house for drum lessons which were an existing responsibility, compared to the AP who made the conscious decision to locate the victim’s residence, ensure she was not around, and travel to her residence for the express purpose of committing the relevant offences. (b)While there were 12 acts of theft in that case, the stolen property was cash (of which full restitution was made), whereas the property in our case was a vibrator – a personal and private item which can cause great embarrassment to the victim, and which was in fact used to cause alarm to her. (c)While the offender in that case faced more charges, the AP faces two charges of criminal trespass and caused alarm to the victim via insulting messages. (d)Viewed holistically, the AP’s case is more egregious, as he had displayed more goal-directedness, undertook preparatory work to commit offences, caused greater harm to the victim, whilst having a greater degree of control over his offending impulses. These factors warrant more emphasis on deterrence and retribution over rehabilitation, unlike the above offender.
